10)\n**1.11 - And Then There Was One (2010)\n*''[[The Good Guys (2010 TV series)|The Good Guys]]''\n**1.09 - Don't Taze Me, Bro (2010)\n**1.16 - Silence of the Dan (2010)\n*''[[The Glades (TV series)|The Glades]]''\n**[[List of The Glades episodes#Season 1 (2010)|1.08 - Marriage Is Murder (2010)]]\n**[[List of The Glades episodes#Season 2 (2011)|2.04 - Moonlighting (2011)]]\n**[[List of The Glades episodes#Season 4 (2013)|4.02 - Shot Girls (2013)]]\n*''[[Burn Notice]]''\n**[[Burn Notice (season 4)|4.14 - Hot Property (2010)]]\n**[[Burn Notice (season 5)|5.06 - Enemy Of My Enemy (2011)]]\n**[[Burn Notice (season 5)|5.17 - Acceptable Loss (2011)]]\n**[[Burn Notice (season 6)|6.09 - Official Business (2012)]]\n**[[Burn Notice (season 7)|7.06 - All or Nothing (2013)]]\n*''[[Bar Karma]]''\n**1.09 - Three Times a Lady (2011)\n*''[[Falling Skies]]''\n**[[Falling Skies (season 3)|3.09 - Journey to Xilbalba (2013)]]\n**[[Falling Skies (season 4)|4.06 - Door Number Three (2014)]]\n**[[Falling Skies (season 5)|5.06 - Respite (2015)]]\n*''[[King & Maxwell]]''\n**1.08 - Job Security (2013)\n*''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''\n**[[The Well (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|1.08 - The Well (2013)]]\n*''[[Switched at Birth (TV series)|Switched at Birth]]''\n**3.06 - The Scream (2014)\n**4.08 - Art Like Love is Dedication (2015)\n*''[[Hit the Floor (TV series)|Hit the Floor]]''\n**[[List of Hit the Floor episodes#Season 2 (2014)|2.03 - Behind the Back (2014)]]\n**[[List of Hit the Floor episodes#Season 2 (2014)|2.04 - Full-Court Press (2014)]]\n*''[[The Librarians (2014 TV series)|The Librarians]]''\n**[[List of The Librarians episodes#Season 1 (2014\u201315)|1.04 - And Santa's Midnight Run (2014)]]\n**[[List of The Librarians episodes#Season 1 (2014\u201315)|1.06 - And the Fables of Doom (2015)]]\n**[[List of The Librarians episodes#Season 1 (2014\u201315)|1.10 - And the Loom of Fate (2015)]]\n**[[List of The Librarians episodes#Season 2 (2015)|2.06 - And the Infernal Contract (2015)]]\n**[[List of The Librarians episodes#Season 2 (2015)|2.08 - And the Point of Salvation (2015)]]\n**3.05 - And the Tears of a Clown (2016)\n**3.06 - And the Trial of the Triangle (2016)\n**3.09 - And the Fatal Separation (2017)\n**4.04 - And the Silver Screen (2017)\n**4.06 - And the Graves of Time (2017)\n*''[[The Orville]]''\n**1.05 - Pria (2017)\n**2.12 - Sanctuary (2019)\n*''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/06/27/star-trek-discovery-jonathan-frakes/|title=Star Trek: Discovery scoop: Jonathan Frakes joins as director|last=Hibberd|first=James|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|location=United States|date=June 27, 2017|accessdate=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n**1.10 - Despite Yourself (2018)\n**2.2 - New Eden (2019)\n**2.9 - Project Daedalus (2019)\n*''[[The Arrangement (2017 TV series)|The Arrangement]]''\n**2.9 - Truth (2018)\n*''[[The Gifted (U.S. TV series)|The Gifted]]''\n**2.13 teMpted (2019)\n*''[[Star Trek: Picard]]''\n**1.04 \"Absolute Candor\" (2020)\n**1.05 \"Stardust City Rag\" (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|408|Jonathan Frakes}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Allmovie name|24630|Jonathan Frakes}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090504131458/http://www.scifitv.com.au/Blog/2009/04/jonathan-frakes-still-number-one/ Jonathan Frakes in-depth interview] at {{URL|http://www.scifitv.com.au/blog|The SCI FI Channel Australia Blog}}\n\n{{Jonathan Frakes}}\n{{The Life Career Award}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frakes, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Liberty High School (Bethlehem, Pennsylvania) alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Belfast, Maine]]\n[[Category:Science fiction film directors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Maine]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Jonathan Frakes\n| image = Jonathan Frakes Photo Op GalaxyCon Minneapolis 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 225px\n| caption = Frakes at [[GalaxyCon]] Minneapolis in 2019\n| known_for = [[William Riker|William T. Riker]]\n| birth_name = Jonathan Scott Frakes\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|8|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bellefonte, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| children = 2\n| years_active = 1978\u2013present\n| occupation = Actor, director\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Genie Francis]]|1988}}\n| residence = [[Calabasas, California]]\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Scott Frakes''' (born August 19, 1952) is an American [[actor]] and [[television director|director]]. Frakes is best known for his portrayal of [[Commander (Star Trek)|Commander]] [[William Riker|William T. Riker]] in the television series ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'' and subsequent films. Frakes also hosted the television series ''[[Beyond Belief: Fact or Fiction]]''. In June 2011, Frakes narrated the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] documentary ''Lee and Grant''. He was the voice for [[David Xanatos]] in the Disney television series ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]''.\n\nFrakes directed while starring in ''[[Star Trek: First Contact]]'' as well as ''[[Star Trek: Insurrection]]''. He directed episodes of several ''[[Star Trek]]'' television series and ''[[The Orville]]''. He is the author of the novel ''The Abductors: Conspiracy''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Abductors: Conspiracy|author=Jonathan Frakes|author2=Dean Wesley Smith|publisher=Tor|location=New York|year=1996|isbn=978-0-312-86208-4}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFrakes was born in [[Bellefonte, Pennsylvania]], the son of Doris J. (n\u00e9e Yingling) and Dr. James R. Frakes. His father was a professor of English literature at [[Lehigh University]] from 1958 to 2001, where he was the Edmund W. Fairchild Professor in American Studies. He also was a critic for the ''[[New York Times Book Review]]'' and book editor until his death in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.mcall.com/2002-03-15/news/3390717_1_fiction-reviews-short-fiction-hudson-review|title=James R. Frakes|newspaper=The Morning Call|location=Allentown, Pennsylvania|date=March 15, 2002|pages=B.10}}</ref> Frakes had a younger brother, Daniel, who died in 1997 from [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.mcall.com/1997-05-19/news/3145857_1_american-cancer-society-memorial-services-bartender|title=Daniel M. Frakes|newspaper=The Morning Call|location=Allentown, Pennsylvania|date=May 19, 1997|page=A09}}</ref>\n\nFrakes grew up in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. A 1970 graduate of Bethlehem's [[Liberty High School (Bethlehem, Pennsylvania)|Liberty High School]], he ran track and played with the Liberty High School Grenadier Band.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sylvia Lawler|title=Jonathan Frakes's career beams up Bethlehem actor scores as 'Star Trek' commander|newspaper=[[The Morning Call]]|location=Allentown, PA|date=September 25, 1988|pages=T.01}}</ref> Frakes received a [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] in Theater Arts at [[Pennsylvania State University]] in 1974, where he was a member of the [[International Thespian Society|Thespians]] and a MA from [[Harvard University]] in 1976.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Stuttgart -Comic Con Germany 2019- 7d by-RaBoe 068.jpg|thumb|Frakes in 2019]]\nFor a time in the 1970s, Frakes worked for [[Marvel Comics]], appearing at conventions in costume as [[Captain America]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2006/07/04/comic-book-urban-legends-revealed-58/|publisher=[[Comics Should Be Good!]]|title=Comic Book Urban Legends Revealed #58|date=2006-07-04|author=Brian Cronin}}</ref> Frakes moved to [[New York City]] and became a member of the [[Impossible Ragtime Theater]]. In that company, Frakes did his first off-Broadway acting in [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s ''[[The Hairy Ape]]'' directed by George Ferencz. His first Broadway appearance was in ''[[Shenandoah (musical)|Shenandoah]]''. At the same time, he landed a role in the [[NBC]] [[soap opera]] ''[[The Doctors (1963 TV series)|The Doctors]]''.<ref name=\"TNGComp18\"/> When his character was dismissed from the show, Frakes moved to [[Los Angeles]] and had guest spots in many of the top television series of the 1970s and 1980s, including ''[[The Waltons]]'' in an episode called \"The Legacy\", ''[[Eight Is Enough]]'', ''[[The Dukes of Hazzard]]'', ''[[Matlock (TV series)|Matlock]]'', \"[[Quincy, ME]]\" in \"The Face of Fear\"  and ''[[Hill Street Blues]]''.\n\nHe played the part of [[Charles Lindbergh]] in a 1983 episode of ''[[Voyagers!]]'' titled \"An Arrow Pointing East\". In 1983, he had a role in the short-lived NBC prime time soap opera ''[[Bare Essence]]'' (which also starred his future wife Genie Francis), and a supporting role in the equally short-lived primetime soap ''[[Paper Dolls]]'' in 1984.<ref name=\"TNGComp18\">{{cite book |last1=Nemecek |first1=Larry |editor1-first=Dave |editor1-last=Stern |title=The Star Trek The Next Generation Companion |year=1992 |publisher=[[Pocket Books]] |location=1230 Avenue of the Americas, New York, NY 10020 |isbn=0-671-79460-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/startreknextgene00neme/page/18 18] |chapter=Rebirth |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/startreknextgene00neme/page/18 }}</ref> He also had recurring roles in ''[[Falcon Crest]]''<ref name=\"TNGComp18\"/> and the [[miniseries]] ''[[North and South (TV miniseries)|North and South]]''. Frakes appeared in the 1986 miniseries ''[[Dream West]]''.\n\nIn 1987 Frakes was cast in the role of Commander William T. Riker on ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sylvia Lawler|newspaper=The Morning Call|title=Making history: \"North and South's\" Jonathan Frakes is crafting his future\u2013 History yields a good part for Jonathan Frakes|location=Allentown, PA|date=May 5, 1986|pages=D.01|url=http://www.jf-fansite.de/interview08.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719050028/http://www.jf-fansite.de/interview08.htm|archivedate=July 19, 2011}}</ref> He was only one of two actors to appear in every episode until the series' conclusion in 1994. He also directed 14 episodes of the show<ref name=\"intl_Frak\">{{Cite web |title=Frakes |author= |work=Star Trek |date= |access-date=30 January 2020 |url= https://intl.startrek.com/database_article/frakes-cast}}</ref> and reprised his role in the spin-off movies, two of which (''[[Star Trek: First Contact]]'' and ''[[Star Trek: Insurrection]]'') he also directed.<ref name=\"intl_Trek\">{{Cite web |title=Trek Directors' School: Jonathan Frakes |author= |work=Star Trek |date= |access-date=30 January 2020 |url= https://intl.startrek.com/article/star-trek-directors-jonathan-frakes-interview}}</ref>\n\nAs well as ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', Frakes has made appearances in ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Voyager]]'', ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'', and ''[[Star Trek: Picard]]''. He is one of only two ''Star Trek'' regulars to appear on five different ''Star Trek'' series. The only other regular to match that number is [[Majel Barrett|Majel Barrett-Roddenberry]]. He has also directed episodes in five of the series (''TNG'', ''DS9,'' ''VOY'', ''DIS'', and ''PIC''). \n\nHe also reprised his role of Riker for a ''Next Generation'' cutaway on [[Peter's Got Woods|an episode of ''Family Guy'']] that also featured his co-stars [[Patrick Stewart]] and [[Michael Dorn]] as their respective roles of [[Jean-Luc Picard|Picard]] and [[Worf]]. Later, he again played himself on another [[Not All Dogs Go to Heaven|''Family Guy'' episode]], where all seven main TNG actors (plus [[Denise Crosby]] and [[Wil Wheaton]]) made voice appearances. He is also one of six Star Trek actors (the other actors being [[Kate Mulgrew]], [[Michael Dorn]], [[George Takei]], [[Avery Brooks]] and [[Majel Barrett]]) to lend their voices to the video game ''Star Trek: Captain's Chair,'' reprising his role as Riker when users visit the ''Enterprise''-D bridge featured in the game. \n\nMuch of Frakes acting work after ''Star Trek'' has been [[animation]] [[voice acting]], most notably voicing the recurring role of [[David Xanatos]] in the animated series ''[[Gargoyles (TV series)|Gargoyles]]'', and he provided the voice of his own head in a jar in the ''[[Futurama]]'' episode \"[[Where No Fan Has Gone Before]]\". He had a small, uncredited role in the 1994 movie ''[[Camp Nowhere]]''. Frakes was also the voice of [[Finn the Human]]'s adult version in the episodes \"Puhoy\" and \"Dungeon Train\" on ''[[Adventure Time]]''.\n\nFrakes was an executive producer for the WB series ''[[Roswell (TV series)|Roswell]]'', directed several episodes, and guest-starred in three episodes. His relationship with ''Star Trek'' is made light of in the [[List of Roswell episodes#Season 3 (2001\u201302)|season 3 episode]] \"Secrets and Lies\", in which the alien character [[Max Evans (Roswell)|Max]] auditions for a guest role as an alien for ''Star Trek: Enterprise''.\n\nFrakes appeared on the 1994 [[Phish]] album ''[[Hoist (album)|Hoist]]'', playing [[trombone]] on the track titled \"Riker's Mailbox\". Frakes would occasionally perform on the trombone during his tenure as Commander Riker, drawing on his college marching band experience. He was also a member of \"The Sunspots\", a vocal backup group of ''Star Trek'' cast members that appeared on [[Brent Spiner]]'s 1991 album ''[[Ol' Yellow Eyes Is Back]]''.\n\nFrakes hosted ''The Paranormal Borderline'', a television series on [[UPN]], which dealt with the paranormal and mysterious happenings and creatures. In one episode, Frakes presented an interview of reporter Yolanda Gaskins with veteran astronaut [[Gordon Cooper]], where they discussed the possibility of aliens having visited Earth in the past.<ref>{{YouTube|dvPR8T1o3Dc}}</ref><ref>[http://www.qtm.net/~geibdan/coop.html http://www.qtm.net/~geibdan/coop.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205120237/http://qtm.net/~geibdan/coop.html |date=2009-02-05 }} UFO Folklore Center \u2013 Transcript of Interview</ref> Overall, the show was criticized and pulled off the air after it was discovered that footage showing a yeti from the Himalayas was purposely faked by the show and its producers. The \"Snowwalker\" footage, as it is known, purportedly shows a yeti crossing through a valley in the Himalayas, walking in front of a Belgian couple who are traversing the area on skis. The network finally admitted the hoax, and Frakes distanced himself from the show. He hosted ''[[Beyond Belief: Fact or Fiction]],'' which also dealt with the paranormal world.\n\nFrakes and Francis appeared together in ''[[Lois & Clark]]'' in the episode \"Don't Tug on Superman's Cape\" as a creepily too-good-to-be-true couple. He narrated the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]]'s ''That's Impossible''.\n\nIn addition to ''Roswell'', Frakes has directed episodes of ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]'',<ref name=\"Press_Kit\">{{cite web|url=http://news.turner.com/press_kits_file.cfm?presskit_id=193&pfile_id=932|title=Leverage Season 3 Episode Synopses|publisher=Turner Network|author=Turner Network|format=[[Microsoft Word]] document|accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]'', ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]'', ''[[Burn Notice]]'', ''[[Falling Skies]]'' and most recently Marvel's ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'', ''[[Switched at Birth (TV series)|Switched at Birth]]'', ''[[Hit the Floor (TV series)|Hit the Floor]]'', ''[[The Librarians (2014 TV series)|The Librarians]]'', and ''[[The Orville]]''.\n\nFrakes works with the Workshops, the Waterfall Arts Center, and the Saltwater Film Society, all located in Maine, where he teaches classes on film direction. He and his wife owned a home furnishings store in [[Belfast, Maine]], called ''The Cherished Home'', which closed in August 2012 due to his wife being too busy with her acting to spend adequate time at the store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=480447481983740&id=106099989418493|title=Log In or Sign Up to View|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFrakes first met actress [[Genie Francis]] on the set of the television soap opera ''[[Bare Essence]]'', and again while filming the mini-series ''[[North and South (TV miniseries)|North and South]]''. They began dating in 1985, became engaged in 1986, and married on May 28, 1988. The couple have two children. They moved from [[Belfast, Maine]], to [[Beverly Hills, California]], in 2008 and later moved to [[Calabasas, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sanfernandovalleyblog.blogspot.com/2013/08/celeb-re-jonathan-frakes-from-star-trek.html|title=Celeb R.E.: Jonathan Frakes from Star Trek and Genie Francis From General Hospital Move to Woodland Hills|first=Marty|last=McFly|work=San Fernando Valley Blogspot|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogger]]|date=August 15, 2013|accessdate=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" | Film\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1994\n| ''[[Camp Nowhere]]''\n| Bob Spiegel\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Star Trek Generations]]''\n|[[Commander William T. Riker]]\n| \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Time Travel Through the Bible''\n| Himself / Host\n|\n