{"title_page": "Spin (1995 film)", "text_new": "{{About|the 1995 film||Spin (disambiguation)}}\n{{advert|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name     = Spin\n|image    =\n|director = [[Brian Springer]]\n|writer   = Brian Springer\n|starring = [[Al Gore]]<br/>[[Bill Clinton]]<br/>[[Barbara Bush]]<br/>[[George H. W. Bush]]<br/>[[Pat Robertson]]<br/>[[Larry Agran]]\n|narrator = Brian Springer\n|released = {{Film date|1995}}\n|runtime  = 56 minutes\n|language = English\n}}\n\n'''''Spin''''' is a 1995 [[documentary film]] by [[Brian Springer]] composed of raw satellite feeds featuring politicians' pre-appearance planning. It covers, not only the [[1992 United States presidential election|presidential election]], but also the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]] as well as the [[Operation Save America|Operation Rescue]] abortion protests.<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/282222/Spin/overview The New York Times]</ref>\n\nUsing the 1992 presidential election as his springboard, Springer captures the behind-the-scenes schemings of politicians and newscasters in the early 1990s. [[Pat Robertson]] banters about \"homos,\" [[Al Gore]] learns how to avoid abortion questions, [[George H. W. Bush]] talks to [[Larry King]] about [[Halcion]]\u2014all presuming they are off camera. Composed of 100% unauthorized satellite footage, ''Spin'' is a surreal expos\u00e9 of media-constructed reality.<ref name=\"art\">{{cite web |title= Spin |publisher= [[Stay Free!]] |url= http://illegal-art.org/video/popups/spin.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20021204011148/http://www.illegal-art.org/video/popups/spin.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2002-12-04 |access-date= 2008-07-24 }}</ref>\n\nThe film also documents behind the scenes footage of [[Larry Agran]] who unsuccessfully sought the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nomination for president. Agran was generally ignored by the media during his candidacy, a topic covered in the documentary. The media did not report his polling numbers even as he met or exceeded the support of other candidates such as [[Jerry Brown]]. Party officials excluded him from most debates on various grounds, even having him arrested when he interrupted to ask to participate. When he managed to join the other candidates in any forum, his ideas went unreported. In photographs with other candidates, he was cropped out. \n\n[[Stephen Holden]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said of the film, \"a devastating critique of television's profound manipulativeness in the way it packages the news and politics\".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/06/arts/critic-s-choice-video-festival-of-an-art-for-life-s-dirtier-nooks.html CRITIC'S CHOICE/VIDEO; Festival of an Art for Life's Dirtier Nooks]</ref> ''Spin'' is a follow-up of the 1992 film ''Feed''; for which Springer provided much of the raw satellite footage.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Media manipulation]]\n* [[Propaganda]]\n* [[Spin (propaganda)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0114512}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/SPINSpringer1995 ''Spin''] at the [[Internet Archive]]\n* [https://www.vdb.org/titles/spin ''Spin''] ([[Video Data Bank]])\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about journalism]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about American politics]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about abortion]]\n[[Category:Films about propaganda]]\n\n\n{{poli-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1995 film||Spin (disambiguation)}}\n{{advert|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name     = Spin\n|image    =\n|director = [[Brian Springer]]\n|writer   = Brian Springer\n|starring = [[Al Gore]]<br/>[[Bill Clinton]]<br/>[[Barbara Bush]]<br/>[[George H. W. Bush]]<br/>[[Pat Robertson]]<br/>[[Larry Agran]]\n|narrator = Brian Springer\n|released = {{Film date|1995}}\n|runtime  = 56 minutes\n|language = English\n}}\n\n'''''Spin''''' is a 1995 [[documentary film]] by [[Brian Springer]] composed of raw satellite feeds featuring politicians' pre-appearance planning. It covers, not only the [[1992 United States presidential election|presidential election]], but also the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]] as well as the [[Operation Save America|Operation Rescue]] abortion protests.<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/282222/Spin/overview The New York Times]</ref>\n\nUsing the 1992 presidential election as his springboard, Springer captures the behind-the-scenes schemings of politicians and newscasters in the early 1990s. [[Pat Robertson]] banters about \"homos,\" [[Al Gore]] learns how to avoid abortion questions, [[George H. W. Bush]] talks to [[Larry King]] about [[Halcion]]\u2014all presuming they are off camera. Composed of 100% unauthorized satellite footage, ''Spin'' is a surreal expos\u00e9 of media-constructed reality.<ref name=\"art\">{{cite web |title= Spin |publisher= [[Stay Free!]] |url= http://illegal-art.org/video/popups/spin.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20021204011148/http://www.illegal-art.org/video/popups/spin.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2002-12-04 |access-date= 2008-07-24 }}</ref>\n\nThe film also documents behind the scenes footage of [[Larry Agran]] who unsuccessfully sought the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nomination for President. Agran was generally ignored by the media during his candidacy, a topic covered in the documentary. The media did not report his polling numbers even as he met or exceeded the support of other candidates such as [[Jerry Brown]]. Party officials excluded him from most debates on various grounds, even having him arrested when he interrupted to ask to participate. When he managed to join the other candidates in any forum, his ideas went unreported. In photographs with other candidates, he was cropped out. \n\n[[Stephen Holden]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said of the film, \"a devastating critique of television's profound manipulativeness in the way it packages the news and politics\".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/06/arts/critic-s-choice-video-festival-of-an-art-for-life-s-dirtier-nooks.html CRITIC'S CHOICE/VIDEO; Festival of an Art for Life's Dirtier Nooks]</ref> ''Spin'' is a follow-up of the 1992 film ''Feed''; for which Springer provided much of the raw satellite footage.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Media manipulation]]\n* [[Propaganda]]\n* [[Spin (propaganda)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0114512}}\n* [https://archive.org/details/SPINSpringer1995 ''Spin''] at the [[Internet Archive]]\n* [https://www.vdb.org/titles/spin ''Spin''] ([[Video Data Bank]])\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about journalism]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about American politics]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about abortion]]\n[[Category:Films about propaganda]]\n\n\n{{poli-documentary-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:replaced: President \u2192 president", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spin_(1995_film)"}
{"title_page": "1993 1. deild karla", "text_new": "The '''1993 season''' of '''[[1. deild karla (football)|1. deild karla]]''' was the 39th season of second-tier football in [[Iceland]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Sigur\u00f0sson |first=V\u00ed\u00f0ir |year=1993 |title=\u00cdslensk knattspyrna 1993 |edition=1st |language=Icelandic |trans-title=Icelandic football 1993}}</ref>\n\n==Standings==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=BRE|name_BRE=[[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]]\n|team2=STJ|name_STJ=[[Stjarnan]]\n|team3=LEI|name_LEI=[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Fjallabygg\u00f0ar|Leiftur]]\n|team4=KA |name_KA =[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Akureyrar|KA]]\n|team5=GRI|name_GRI=[[Knattspyrnudeild UMFG|Grindav\u00edk]]\n|team6=\u00deR\u00d3|name_\u00deR\u00d3=[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 \u00der\u00f3ttur|\u00der\u00f3ttur R.]]\n|team7=KFF|name_KFF=[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Fjar\u00f0abygg\u00f0ar|\u00der\u00f3ttur N.]]\n|team8=\u00cdR |name_\u00cdR =[[\u00cd\u00fer\u00f3ttaf\u00e9lag Reykjav\u00edkur|\u00cdR]]\n|team9=B\u00cd|name_B\u00cd=[[B\u00cd/Bolungarv\u00edk|B\u00cd]]\n|team10=TIN|name_TIN=[[Tindast\u00f3ll]]\n|win_BRE=12|draw_BRE=2|loss_BRE=4|gf_BRE=36|ga_BRE=14\n|win_STJ=11|draw_STJ=4|loss_STJ=3|gf_STJ=39|ga_STJ=19\n|win_LEI=11|draw_LEI=3|loss_LEI=4|gf_LEI=33|ga_LEI=25\n|win_KA =9|draw_KA =2|loss_KA =7|gf_KA =31|ga_KA =22\n|win_GRI=7|draw_GRI=6|loss_GRI=5|gf_GRI=29|ga_GRI=21\n|win_\u00deR\u00d3=8|draw_\u00deR\u00d3=3|loss_\u00deR\u00d3=7|gf_\u00deR\u00d3=31|ga_\u00deR\u00d3=26\n|win_KFF=5|draw_KFF=2|loss_KFF=11|gf_KFF=24|ga_KFF=45\n|win_\u00cdR =4|draw_\u00cdR =4|loss_\u00cdR =10|gf_\u00cdR =20|ga_\u00cdR =34\n|win_B\u00cd=4|draw_B\u00cd=3|loss_B\u00cd=11|gf_B\u00cd=20|ga_B\u00cd=37\n|win_TIN=3|draw_TIN=3|loss_TIN=12|gf_TIN=20|ga_TIN=40\n\n|col_P=green1|text_P=Promoted to [[1994 \u00darvalsdeild]]\n|result1=P|result2=P\n|col_R=red1|text_R=Relegated to [[1994 2. deild karla|1994 2. deild]]\n|result9=R|result10=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n==Top scorers==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Scorer\n!Goals\n!Team\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} Ingvar \u00d3lason\n|align=center|10\n|[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 \u00der\u00f3ttur|\u00der\u00f3ttur R.]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} P\u00e9tur Bj\u00f6rn J\u00f3nsson\n|align=center|10\n|[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Fjallabygg\u00f0ar|Leiftur]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} Leifur Geir Hafsteinsson\n|align=center|10\n|[[Stjarnan]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} \u00de\u00f3rarinn \u00d3lafsson\n|align=center|9\n|[[Knattspyrnudeild UMFG|Grindav\u00edk]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} Gunnar M\u00e1r M\u00e1sson\n|align=center|9\n|[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Fjallabygg\u00f0ar|Leiftur]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} [[Willum \u00de\u00f3r \u00de\u00f3rsson]]\n|align=center|9\n|[[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1. deild karla seasons}}\n\n[[Category:1. deild karla (football) seasons]]\n[[Category:1992\u201393 in European second tier association football leagues|Iceland]]\n[[Category:1993\u201394 in European second tier association football leagues|Iceland]]\n[[Category:1993 in Icelandic football|2]]\n", "text_old": "The '''1993 season''' of '''[[1. deild karla (football)|1. deild karla]]''' was the 39th season of second-tier football in [[Iceland]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Sigur\u00f0sson |first=V\u00ed\u00f0ir |year=1993 |title=\u00cdslensk knattspyrna 1993 |edition=1st |language=Icelandic |trans-title=Icelandic football 1993}}</ref>\n\n==Standings==\n{{fb cl header}}\n|-\n|1||[[Brei\u00f0ablik UBK|Brei\u00f0ablik]]||18||12||2||4||36||14||+22||38||align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[Promoted]] to [[1994 \u00darvalsdeild]]\n|-\n|2||[[Stjarnan]]||18||11||4||3||39||19||+20||37 \n|-\n|3||[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Fjallabygg\u00f0ar|Leiftur]]||18||11||3||4||33||25||+8||36 \n|-\n|4||[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lag Akureyrar|KA]]||18||9||2||7||31||22||+9||29\n|-\n|5||[[Knattspyrnudeild UMFG|Grindav\u00edk]]||18||7||6||5||29||21||+8||27\n|-\n|6||[[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 \u00der\u0